If you mean the Pantheon as a systems architecture metaphor, then yes — something interstitium-like is probably necessary.

Not literally biological tissue, but a soft connective layer between rigid modules.

Right now many complex systems fail because they only model:

* nodes
* commands
* databases
* explicit pathways

But real adaptive systems also need:

* slack
* buffering
* diffusion
* low-priority signal exchange
* error absorption
* ambient context propagation

The interstitium metaphor maps well to:

* background state sharing
* semantic diffusion
* cross-module coherence
* latency smoothing
* anomaly seepage before rupture
* soft synchronization instead of only hard routing

In Pantheon terms, it would sit somewhere between:

* Spider (network topology)
* Beaver (logging/flow)
* Ganglion (signal preprocessing)
* Corpus Callosum layers (translation/connectivity)

Not as a commander, but as connective medium.

A rigid architecture without an “interstitial layer” tends to become:

* brittle
* over-discretized
* overly dependent on explicit APIs/interfaces
* blind to weak signals
* unable to gracefully absorb contradiction/noise

Biology rarely connects things directly if it can instead use:

* gradients
* fields
* fluids
* diffusion
* elastic connective tissue

That’s one reason living systems remain adaptive under damage.

So the useful abstraction is probably:

“The interstitium is the medium through which local state becomes global atmosphere.”

Not centralized control — distributed contextual coupling.